Introduction

The data includes basic information of customers of a telecommunication company along with services they have signed up for. It comes in four chunks. Two of them are related to basic information and the other two show the usage of the services they signed up for. The aim of this analysis is to fit a model to predict the churn rate of the customers using the basic information and the usage of services. In this analysis we are going to fit logistic regression using Glm function. Since the regression models provide very high interpretability by providing coefficients and standard errors, as well as test statistics, I decided to proceed with the regression model. Additionally, I will show my approach on checking model assumptions, other than the predictability of the model. Checking model assumptions, such as linearity, independence, normality (errors are normally distributed) and constant variance helps us to have more accurate coefficients in case we are interested in using interpretability of the model. Also, it allows us to check how much we can rely on the result of the model and to compare predictability or interpretability of several models.

In this part, I used SQL script to join the customers demographic and usage data. Depending on the size of the data set, there are different ways that might be faster or slower.

customer <- sqldf("SELECT *

Exploratory data analysis

In this section I checked the distribution of the continuous variables, as well as categorical variables. This is to deteremine if they are following normal distribution, in case we would like to rely on confidence interval in the future for model assumptions. Also, it helps to have a general overview of our data to help us further on in the analysis.

ggplot(customer,aes(x=customer$`Age in years`,group=customer$churn,fill=customer$churn))+
  geom_histogram(position="dodge",binwidth=1)+theme_bw()

Most of the customers are between 30 to 45. Most of the customers who churn are around their mid 30s.

ggplot(customer,aes(x=customer$`Months with service`,group=customer$churn,fill=customer$churn))+
  geom_histogram(position="dodge",binwidth=1)+theme_bw()

Customers seems to churn within the first 20 months of the service. The distribution of customers who churned is positively skewed and very different from customers who did not churn. The number of customers who did not churn seems very spread out (with a slight negative skew). There are few peaks in the distribution which show a number of counts on 50 and 70 is higher, implying most of the current customers have been with the company for at least more than 4 years (50 months).

ggplot(customer,aes(x=customer$`Number of people in household`,group=customer$churn,fill=customer$churn))+
  geom_histogram(position="dodge",binwidth=1)+theme_bw()

The number of people in the household definitely does not follow normal distribution and we can clearly see Benfords law in this distribution. Additionally, it shows both churned and not churned are having a positive skew (irrelevant of whether they are churned or not). This shows, particularly this variable, might not be our interest. However, I would wait and verify that in the next stages.

ggplot(customer,aes(x=customer$`Household income in thousands`,group=customer$churn,fill=customer$churn))+
  geom_histogram(position="dodge",binwidth=10)+theme_bw()+ 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = round(seq(min(customer$`Household income in thousands`), max(customer$`Household income in thousands`), by = 91),1))

Looking at household income (rescaled the x-axis for better readability), no matter whether churned or not, customers are having more counts around 38 thousands, forming heavily positive skewed distribution for both categories. However, the wide range of this distribution is noticeable.

Checking Normality using QQnorm plot

qqnorm(customer$`Age in years`);qqline(customer$`Age in years`)

qqnorm(customer$`Household income in thousands`);qqline(customer$`Household income in thousands`)

qqnorm(customer$`Toll free last month`);qqline(customer$`Toll free last month`)

Checking normality of variables can be helpful at this stage as they might help us with model assumptions. However, normality will be checked for the best model on the residuals in the models assessment stage. Here, as an instance we can see normality does not apply for the three chosen variables (Age in years,Household income in thousands and Toll free last month).

Looking at the first plot of age in years variable, we might assume normality (However, such situations can be fixed by bootstraping or collecting more data). In order to verify the graphical evidence, we can use the Shapiro test to check normality further.

shapiro.test(customer$`Age in years`)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  customer$`Age in years`
## W = 0.97694, p-value = 1.678e-11
shapiro.test(customer$`Age in years`[customer$churn=="No"])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  customer$`Age in years`[customer$churn == "No"]
## W = 0.98367, p-value = 5.524e-08

Looking at the result of the Shapiro test with H Null, assuming normality for the customers who did not churn and all the customers age, we can see the extremely small p-value shows the significance of test statistics. We can reject the Null Hypothesis and verify none-normality in this particular distribution.

Correlation

At this stage, I check for correlations between variables as well as correlation in the model residuals (next stages), as correlation can affect the model coefficient if interested in interpreting coefficients and standard errors. However, this might not affect the prediction. Looking at the number of variables, I noticed some of the variables seems to be related to each other and explain the same variability. For instance, I noticed toll free service, which is zero and one, is describing the same variability as toll free last months variable. Whenever it is one, the toll free last month variable has values and, whenever not, it is zero. The same goes to equipment rental and equipment last month (equipment over tenure which is removed already after assessing correlation). Therefore, I decide to get rid of equipment rental. Same goes with calling card service vs calling card over tenure or calling card over last month as well as wireless service and wireless over tenure and wireless last month.

With the help of the below plot and manual observation, I removed the related variables:

customer %>%
  dplyr::select (`Months with service`,`Age in years`,`Years at current address`,  `Household income in thousands`, 
                 `Years with current employer`,`Number of people in household`, `Long distance last month`,
                  `Toll free last month`, `Equipment last month`, `Calling card last month`,
                 `Wireless last month`, `Long distance over tenure`, `Toll free over tenure`,
                 `Equipment over tenure`, `Calling card over tenure`, `Wireless over tenure`) -> cor1
corrplot(cor(cor1), method = "color",tl.col = "black", number.cex = 0.7, type = "lower",
         addCoef.col = "black",tl.srt = 30)

As shown in the plot, it is clear that all of the variables ending with over tenure have very strong collinearity with their pairs, variables ending with last months. Therefore, I decided to remove the ones with ending over tenure as some of those had collinearity with other variables.

Since I suspected we might have problems when fitting the Glm model using the number of variables, I decided to remove collinearities further in order to help the algorithm to converge. Also months with service has collinearity with multiple variables that helps us to decide to remove it as well as Years at current address, Years with current employer and Wireless last month. Finally, the remaining highest collinearity is 0.39 which can be seen in the below illustration.

customer %>%
  dplyr::select (`Household income in thousands`,`Number of people in household`, `Long distance last month`,
                 `Toll free last month`, `Equipment last month`, `Calling card last month`) -> cor2
                corrplot(cor(cor2), method = "color",tl.col = "black", number.cex = 0.7, type = "lower",addCoef.col = "black",tl.srt = 30)

Defining colours for plots:

Assessing categorical variables with Yes or No options (binomial)

ggplot(cat3)+

  facet_wrap(~columns)+

  theme_dark()

There are major differences in churn or not churn between customers who have calling card service, electric billing, equipment rental (very significant), internet, retired and voice mail. While the churn rates does not seem to be drastically different in other categories.

Looking at the proportion of internet and electric billing we can see that those who do not have internet might not use electric billing which is a common sense. So these two variables can have a very high correlation. However by knowing more about variables description, it would be easier to find such collinearities. At this stage, I do not have enough information to quickly assess it. However, I believe one can have internet and not enable electric billing! So, I leave this when checking for correlation in the model.

Additionally, by knowing more details of the variables, we probably can categorize some of the continuous variables to acquire better predictability which can be tested separately.

Model Fitting

Logistic Regression

Setting up parralellisation

cores <- makeCluster(detectCores()-2)
registerDoParallel(cores = cores)

creating new data frame without customer ID

cus <- subset(customer, select = -c(Customer))

Creating Dummy variables for (yes/no) binomial variables

cus %>% mutate(Churn = ifelse(cus$churn == "Yes", 1, 0)) -> cus
cus %>% mutate(marital_status = ifelse(cus$`Marital status` == "Married", 1, 0)) -> cus
cus %>% mutate(retired = ifelse(cus$Retired == "Yes", 1, 0)) -> cus
cus %>% mutate(gender = ifelse(cus$Gender== "Female", 1, 0)) -> cus
cus %>% mutate(toll_free_service = ifelse(cus$`Toll free service`== "Yes", 1, 0)) -> cus
cus %>% mutate(equipment_rental = ifelse(cus$`Equipment rental`== "Yes", 1, 0)) -> cus
cus %>% mutate(calling_card_service = ifelse(cus$`Calling card service`== "Yes", 1, 0)) -> cus
cus %>% mutate(wireless_service = ifelse(cus$`Wireless service`== "Yes", 1, 0)) -> cus
cus %>% mutate(multiple_lines = ifelse(cus$`Multiple lines`== "Yes", 1, 0)) -> cus
cus %>% mutate(voice_mail = ifelse(cus$`Voice mail`== "Yes", 1, 0)) -> cus

Removing redundant variables that we do not need anymore:

cus <- dplyr::select(cus, - c(churn, `Marital status`, Retired, Gender, `Toll free service`,`Equipment rental`,
                      `Calling card service`,`Wireless service`,`Multiple lines`,`Voice mail`,
                      `Paging service`,Internet,`Caller ID`,`Call waiting`,`Call waiting`,
                      `Call forwarding`,`Three way calling`,`Electronic billing`))

At this stage we split data in train and test sets, since the data set is imbalanced we get help from createpartition function to pick up churn rates in an equal proportion for train and test sets.

set.seed(1234)
train.indices <- createDataPartition(cus$Churn, p=0.7, list = FALSE)
train <- cus[train.indices,]
holdout <- cus[-train.indices,]

Verifying if the train and holdout data has a close proportion of churn rate

train %>%
  summarise(Total_Obs = n(), Churn_num = sum(Churn == 1), Churn_prop = Churn_num/Total_Obs)
##   Total_Obs Churn_num Churn_prop
## 1       700       127  0.1814286
# Total_Obs Churn_num Churn_prop
# 1       700       123  0.1757143
holdout %>%

ROC curve with AUC and Confidence Interval

pROC_obj <- roc(train$Churn,train_prob,

In this ROC Curve, I decided to compute the confidence interval (CI) of the sensitivity at the given specificity points. By default, the 95% CI are computed with 2000 stratified bootstrap replicates. The AUC is 0.954 with (0.936-0.971) 95% confidence interval.

The AUC is 0.958 with (0.935-0.981) confidence interval. After assessing the model with 0.5 threshold. I proceed to find the optimal threshold for the model. So, then I can improve the performance.

I create a prediction object using prediction and true class label and evaluate the predictors using performance function over prediction object, created already.

GLMprediction <- prediction(train_prob, train_actual)
GLMperformance <- performance(GLMprediction, "spec", "sens")

Then I extract the cutoffs and determine where the alpha is minimum when checking the difference of specificity and sensitivity which is our optimal cutoff:

ALLcutoffs <- data.frame(alpha_value=GLMperformance@alpha.values[[1]], 
                         specificity=GLMperformance@x.values[[1]],
                         sensitivity= GLMperformance@y.values[[1]])
opt_cutoff <- ALLcutoffs[which.min(abs(ALLcutoffs$specificity-ALLcutoffs$sensitivity)),]
obj1 <- xyplot(ALLcutoffs$specificity ~ alpha_value, ALLcutoffs, type = "l" , lwd=2, ylab = "Specificity")
obj2 <- xyplot(ALLcutoffs$sensitivity ~ alpha_value, ALLcutoffs, type = "l", lwd=2, ylab = "Sensitivity")
doubleYScale(obj1, obj2, text = c("Specificity", "Sensitivity") , add.ylab2 = TRUE) +
  latticeExtra::layer(panel.text(x=0.25, y=0.75, label="Optimal Cutoff point \n0.2189511 (0.222)"))

Now, I set the predictions according to the obtained cutoff point (0.222):

optcut_train_prob <- predict(stepGLM3, data = train, type = "response") 
optcut_train_pred   <- factor(ifelse(train_prob >= 0.222, "Yes", "No"))
optcut_train_actual <- factor(ifelse(train$Churn == 1, "Yes", "No"))

Assessing influential points

plot(stepGLM3, which =4)
abline(h=4/nrow(customer),lty=2)

Assessing the Cooks distance and using the rule of thumb of 4 divided by the number of data points (the dotted horizontal line). There are few influential points. This can be addressed by adding more predictors to the model or checking the data collection.

plot(stepGLM3, which = 5, add.smooth = TRUE, cook.levels = c(4/1000, 0.5, 1))

To further investigate any influential residuals (above), I decided to plot them against leverage and 3 criteria: first, 4 over number of rows; second, 0.5 and finally, 1. There are few points that exceeded the first rule, however, there are no other points beyond the second and third limit.

plot(stepGLM3, which = 6, add.smooth = TRUE, cook.levels = c(4/1000, 0.5, 1))

Comparing the plots of the leverage against standard residuals and the Cooks distance against leverage, it can be determined if the influential points are considered because of high residuals or Cooks distance. For instance point 670 shows the largest Cooks distance due to high residuals and can be confirmed that it is a high leverage. On the other hand point 890 just misses to be the high influential point even though it has high residuals.

plot(stepGLM3, which =c(1,2,3))

Looking at the rest of the diagnosis plots of residuals, even though there is good accuracy, the normality assumption is violated, and I am getting some confirmation of over fitted model in some parts. As there are patterns in the residuals and there are no sparse residuals vs fitted values, this can imply the coefficients and standard errors might not be very reliable.

Another graphical assessment can be checking observed values and fitted (predicted). I could assess the fit of the model by plotting the observed values vs the fitted values as shown below, but this is relatively uninformative since the response values are binary and the fitted values are probabilities. When the response values are proportions, this comparison is of more use. Cross checking the residual plots and the below plot, gives me a feeling of slight over-fit in parts of the data points.

observed <- stepGLM3$fitted.values + stepGLM3$residuals
plot(stepGLM3$fitted.values, observed)

R Squared

Therefore, I decided to check R squared for measure of our binary data. I calculated R squared as a measure of goodness of fit as below which gives us a fairly good number 0.71, showing the variability in the response can be explained by our predictors up to 71 percent.

(1-exp((stepGLM3$deviance-stepGLM3$null.deviance)/1000))/(1-exp(-stepGLM3$null.deviance/1000))
## [1] 0.6453555

Assessing model constant variance

Constant variance Plot

spreadLevelPlot(stepGLM3)

## 
## Suggested power transformation:  0.4991498

This plot shows slightly none constant variance for large fitted values for absolute residuals. In order to be certain I ran a statistical test to feel more confident about noticing any possible issues (as below).

Breush-Pagan test

bptest(stepGLM3)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  stepGLM3
## BP = 366.15, df = 6, p-value < 2.2e-16

Breush Pagan tests p-value shows evidence against null hypothesis of none constant variance (homoskedasticity) so I might dismiss any none constant error variance issues at this stage. In case of being concerned about the slight none constant error variance, I might consider using GLS models in the future.

Assessing residual independence

acf plot to check if there is any correlation in residuals:

acf(residuals(stepGLM3), main = "Best Model - Autocorrelation")

acf plot shows there is no correlation in the residuals, except a very slight peak at lag 7 or 8 which can be looked at if needed.

Durbin Watson test

To be sure about any correlation in residuals I ran a Durbin Watson test in case we do not want to highly rely on plots and graphical assessments.

durbinWatsonTest(stepGLM3)
##  lag Autocorrelation D-W Statistic p-value
##    1     0.009870035      1.979732   0.784
##  Alternative hypothesis: rho != 0

The null hypothesis of this test is, there is no correlations. So I happily fail to reject H null and it shows we dont have correlation and per test statistics of 1.912527 I might have a slight positive correlation as it is just below 2 (D-W test statistic is between 0 to 4 with 2 representing no correlation).

Future work

During the analysis I mentioned a few possible actions that can be taken to review the model fitting. However, at this stage, there are issues that have been highlighted and would be worth investigating. More information about the variables would help to discard some of the correlations. The models seem to be over-fitted in the majority of fitted values. This can be because of too few parameters, data collection or getting rid of the variables in an inefficient way which requires a constant back and forth procedure to diagnose. It seems that there are very few negative residuals, which can be looked at and refitted using log-link, clog-clog or squared functions.

Lastly, I would compare any successful model with, tree, random forest, XGBoost and Naive Bayes. So, we can assess models from different prospective as well as importance of the variables.
